sec.p:
The DWOA enhances the conventional optimization based on Lévy flight, which is a stochastic movement strategy with an abrupt change in direction and extended travel distances. The approach enhances global search, avoids premature convergence, and enhances solution precision in energy optimization problems. For managing the energy of the smart grid, DWO performs position updates using Lévy flight to better manage energy resources, optimize renewable energy dispatch, and improve system stability. Dynamic adjustment of energy scheduling lowers electricity bills, PAR, and $C O_{2}$ emissions. Lévy flight in DWO is expressed in (1) as follows:
\begin{equation*}
L F=0.01 \times \frac{v \times \sigma}{|u\vert^{\frac{1}{2}}}, \sigma=\left(\frac{\Gamma(1+\Upsilon) \times \sin \left(\frac{\pi \gamma}{2}\right)}{\Gamma\left(\frac{1+\gamma}{2}\right) \times \gamma \times 2\left(\frac{\gamma-1}{2}\right)}\right)^{\frac{1}{\gamma}}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
Where $v$ and $u$ are random variables in (0,1), integrating randomness into the search process. Using Lévy flights, the EWO algorithm improves the energy management model to offer maximum power distribution, efficient use of the grid, and renewable utilization of energy.

GOA is also utilized in the IEM model for power supply scheduling within smart grids that consist of a combination of RES and BSS. GOA relies on natural gazelle foraging and evasive behavior to perform energy scheduling, lower electricity costs, and ensure grid stability. This model simulates the movement of the gazelles in the solution space in different energy distribution situations. The most powerful gazelles (Elite solutions) control the power optimization distribution for maximizing the energy content of RES, BSS, and grid supply. The following (2) is the elite matrix for the optimal energy allocation.
\begin{equation*}
\text { Elite }=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
w_{1,1}^{\prime} & w_{1,2}^{\prime} & \cdots & w_{1, c}^{\prime} \\
w_{2,1}^{\prime} & w_{2,2}^{\prime} & \cdots & w_{2, c}^{\prime} \\
\vdots & \vdots & & \vdots \\
w_{m, 1}^{\prime} & w_{m, 2}^{\prime} & \cdots & w_{m, c}^{\prime}
\end{array}\right]
\tag{2}
\end{equation*}

The modified energy distribution is represented by the following (3) as follows.
\begin{align*}
& \textit { gazeller }+1=\textit { gazellet }+t \cdot Q \cdot Q A \cdot(\textit { elitet }-Q A \cdot \\
& \textit { gazellet }) \tag{3}
\end{align*}
Where $Q A$ stands for Brownian motion in adaptive energy allocation, $Q$ is a random variable, and $t$ is the adjustment factor. Even though the grid experiences fluctuations (such as when there are predators), the algorithm automatically adjusts energy scheduling with Lévy flight motion in (4).
\begin{align*}
& \textit { gazeller }+1=\textit { gazellet }+T \cdot \mu \cdot Q K \cdot(\textit { Elitet }-Q K \cdot \\
& \textit { gazellet }) \tag{4}
\end{align*}
Where the grid response rate is $T$, and $Q K$ depends on real-time load changes. The adaptive demand response control starts with cumulative grid supply and demand variations, and these are presented as follows in (5).
\begin{equation*}
D E=\left(1-\frac{s}{S}\right)^{\frac{2 s}{S}}
\tag{5}
\end{equation*}

The real energy cost per time interval was determined on a Real-Time Pricing rate. Energy cost per hour is determined by the following (6).
\begin{equation*}
\zeta(s)=\left(\Gamma_{u}(s)+\Gamma_{E}(s)\right) \times F O(s)
\tag{6}
\end{equation*}
Where $\Gamma_{u}^{s}$ and $\Gamma_{t g}^{s}$ stand for the energy usage of stationary and movable appliances, respectively. The cost of power per day may be determined as follows in (7). Equations (8-9) represent the supplied power from BSS and RES. Equation (10) provides the entire quantity of power consumed.
\begin{equation*}
\zeta(S)=\sum_{s=1}^{S}\left(\Gamma_{u}^{S}(S)+\Gamma_{E}^{S}(S)\right) \times F O(s)
\tag{7}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
\emptyset(s)=\left(\Gamma_{m t}+\Gamma_{t g}(s)\right)-\left(F(s)+\right. \text{BSS}. \left.\alpha_{b s s}(s)\right). \tag{8}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
\emptyset(s)=\begin{cases}\emptyset(s), \quad \text { if } \emptyset(s) \geq 0 \\ 0, \quad \text { moreover }\end{cases}
\tag{9}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
\delta(S)=\sum_{s=1}^{S}(\emptyset(s) \times F O(s)) \tag{10}
\end{equation*}

PAR: To reduce PAR, the IEM Model tries to optimize the use of energy. This is by RES, BSS, and EG. PAR for $M$ consumers can be calculated using (11) as follows:
\begin{equation*}
\delta(S)=\frac{\max \left(F_{\text {total }}(s)\right)}{\frac{1}{S} \sum_{m=1}^{M}\left(\sum_{s=1}^{M} F_{\text {total }}(s, m)\right.} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}

$\text{CO}_{2}$ Emission: The carbon produced by using power is displayed in (12). Where $F O_{\text {avg }}, \eta, \gamma$, and $n$ stand for the average monthly energy bill, price per $k W h$ of $0.20, electricity emission factor equivalent of 1.37, and calendar month, respectively.
\begin{equation*}
\theta(s)=\frac{F O_{\text {avg }}}{\eta \times \gamma \times n} \tag{12}
\end{equation*}

$E G$: The smart building purchases energy from the EG at an established bill, as detailed in the subsequent sentence. The structure receives its energy from its external electricity system. Let $F_{f w}(s)$ show how much electricity was taken from the power grid at a certain time $s$, (13).
\begin{equation*}
0 \leq F_{f w}(s) \leq F_{f w, \max } \tag{13}
\end{equation*}

RES: RES with wind power refers to collect wind energy using turbines to create electricity. Wind turbines generate electricity based on wind speed, which is influenced by environmental factors and path of the wind. The quantity of energy produced by a wind turbine is estimated using the following (14).
\begin{equation*}
O_{x c}(s)=\frac{1}{2} * \rho * B_{s c} * U_{t}(s)^{3}
\tag{14}
\end{equation*}

BSS: BSS accommodates excess RE to be used as a recovery in high-demand times such that the charging and discharging processes are optimized. Stored energy at time $s$ is expressed as the following (15).
\begin{equation*}
B S(s)=B S(s-1)+l \cdot \delta^{B S} \cdot F O^{d g}(s)-\frac{l \cdot F O^{c d g}(s)}{\delta^{B S}}
\tag{15}
\end{equation*}
Where $B S(s)$ is stored energy, $l$ is the duration of a time slot, $\delta^{B S}$ is the BSS efficiency, $F O^{d g}(s)$ is charging power, and $F O^{c d g}(s)$ is discharging power. To keep the battery healthy and avoid overcharging or deep discharge, the system using (16-18) as follows:
\begin{equation*}
F O^{d g}(s) \leq F O_{V A}^{d g}
\tag{16}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
F O^{c d g}(s) \leq F O_{K A}^{c d g} \tag{17}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
B S S(s) \leq F T_{V A}^{d g} \tag{18}
\end{equation*}
